  "prompt": "How can I define bijection between (0,1) and (0,1]?",
  "response": "To define a bijection between the open interval (0,1) and the half-open interval (0,1], you can use a carefully constructed function. Here's one approach:\n\n1) First, consider the function f: (0,1) \u2192 (0,1]\n\nf(x) = 1 - 1/x\n\nProof that this is a bijection:\n\nInjective (one-to-one):\n- Let f(a) = f(b)\n- 1 - 1/a = 1 - 1/b\n- 1/a = 1/b\n- a = b\n\nSurjective (onto):\n- For any y \u2208 (0,1], y = f(1/(1-y))\n  Because 1/(1-y) is always in (0,1)\n\nThe inverse function is:\nf^(-1)(y) = 1/(1-y)\n\nThis function maps:\n- Every x \u2208 (0,1) uniquely to a point in (0,1]\n- Every point in (0,1] can be obtained by this mapping\n\nThus, f establishes a bijection between (0,1) and (0,1].",
